Field theory is an alternative methodology to micro- and macro-analyses of society, focusing on the spaces in which jockeying for social position occurs.
Three of the most developed field theories:
The 1983 theory of organizational fields (neo-institutionalism) developed by DiMaggio and Powell.
Strategic action fields put forth by Fligstein and McAdam in 2012.
How these three theories address two crucial questions in sociology: (1) how social fields emerge, change, and reproduce and (2) how to understand agency and actors.
